<exercise label="nth-term-divergence">
  <title>True/False</title>
  <idx>vector space</idx>
  <statement correct="no">
    <p>
      Suppose <m>\{a_n\}_{n=1}^{\infty}</m> is a sequence such that <m>\lim_{n\to\infty} a_n = 0</m>. Can you conclude that the series <m>\sum_{n=1}^{\infty} a_n</m> converges?
    </p>
  </statement>
  <feedback>
    <p>
        Check your notes from last class to find a counterexample.
    </p>
  </feedback>
  <hint>
    <p>
        The fact that <m>\lim_{x\to\infty} f(x) = 0</m> does not imply <m>\int_{a}^{\infty}f(x)\,dx</m> necessarily converges. You can apply the integral test to series.
    </p>
  </hint>
</exercise>

