<exercise>
  <statement>
    <p>
      Here is an example of a Parson's problem for a proof that a series converges. There are many problem types that can be authored
    </p>
    <p>
      The problem is to decide if <m>\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\frac{(-1)^{n+1}}{n}</m> converges.
    </p>
  </statement>
  <!--Block order is where they appear in your choices, the order you put them in is correct.-->
  <blocks>
  <block order="2">
    <p>
    This series is of the form <m>\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}(-1)^{n+1}a_n</m>, where <m>a_n = \frac{1}{n}</m>.
    </p>
  </block>
  <block order="1" correct="no">
  <p>
    Since <m>\lim_{n\to\infty} \frac{(-1)^{n+1}}{n} = 0</m>, this series converges.
  </p>
  </block>
  <block order="5">
  <p>
    <m>0 &lt; \frac{1}{n+1} &lt; \frac{1}{n} </m>, i.e. the sequence of absolute values is positive and decreasing.
  </p>
  </block>
  <block order="4">
  <p>
    <m>\lim_{n\to\infty}\frac{1}{n} = 0</m>
  </p>
  </block>
  <block order="3">
  <p>
   Thus, this series converges by the Alternating Series Test.
  </p>
  </block>
  </blocks>


</exercise>

